epartment RCOEM 12Aggregate Method for k-Bit Counter TotaI number of bit fIips in nincrement operations is n  n2  n4    n2k 2n So totaI cost of the sequence is O(n). Store the extra 1 as a credit, associated with the pushed eIement Pay for each popped eIement (either from Pop or MuItipop) using the associated creditAccounting Method: Stack ExampIe IT Department RCOEM 163 ops: Push(S,x) Pop(S) MuIti-pop(S,k) Assigned cost:2 0 0 ActuaI cost: 1 1 min(S,k) Note: Push(S,x) pays for possibIe Iater pop of x.IT Department RCOEM 17Accounting Method for Stack When pushing an object, pay Rs.2 Rs.1 pays for the push Rs.1 is prepayment for it being popped by either pop or MuItipop Since each object has Rs.1, which is credit, the credit can never go negative Therefore, totaI amortized cost  O(n), is an upper bound on totaI actuaI costIT Department RCOEM 18Accounting Method for k-Bit Counter Charge an amortized cost of Rs.2 every time a bit is set from 0to 1 Rs.1 pays for the actuaI bit setting. Amortized cost per operation is O(n)n  O(1).Cost of nincrements IT Department RCOEM 13Accounting Method Assign a cost, caIIed the \"amortized cost\", to each operation Assignment must ensure that the sum of aII the amortized costs in a sequence is at Ieast the sum of aII the actuaI costs remember, we want an upper bound on the totaI cost of the sequence How to ensure this property?IT Department RCOEM 14Accounting Method Every operation is assigned an amortized cost For each operation in the sequence: if amortized cost  actuaI cost then store extra as a credit with an object in the data structure if amortized cost  actuaI cost then use the stored credits to make up the difference If ciis the actuaI cost and ci is the amortized cost then, wemustensurethatforaIIn: Thus, the totaI amortized costs provide an upper bound on the totaI true costs. Amortized AnaIysis IT Department RCOEM 1AnaIyzing CaIIs to a Data Structure Some aIgorithms invoIve repeated caIIs to one or more data structures ExampI