2025-05-27 00:30:09,420 - __main__ - DEBUG - Generated flashcards: [
  {
    "question": "What is the amortized analysis strategy of overcharging operations?",
    "answer": "It is a method where some operations are intentionally charged more than their actual cost, with the extra 'prepaid' amount used to pay for future operations."
  },
  {
    "question": "How does prepaid charging help in amortized analysis?",
    "answer": "Prepaid charging accumulates extra cost during certain operations so that it can cover more expensive operations later, ensuring the average (amortized) cost per operation remains low."
  },
  {
    "question": "What is the Aggregate Method in amortized analysis?",
    "answer": "The Aggregate Method involves first analyzing the entire sequence of operations and then calculating the amortized cost per operation by dividing the worst-case total cost T(n) by the number of operations n."
  },
  {
    "question": "How does the Potential Method work in amortized analysis?",
    "answer": "The Potential Method assigns amortized costs based on a potential function that maps the state of the data structure to a real number, ensuring the sum of amortized costs for all operations is at least the sum of the actual costs, plus the net change in potential between the initial and final states."
  },
  {
    "question": "What is X?",
    "answer": "X is..."
  },
  {
    "question": "How does Y work?",
    "answer": "Y works by..."
  },
  {
    "question": "What is the Potential Method in amortized analysis?",
    "answer": "The Potential Method maintains credit as potential energy associated with the data structure as a whole, spreading the cost of operations over a sequence so that the cost of each will be T(n) divided by n."
  },
  {
    "question": "How does the Accounting Method work in amortized analysis?",
    "answer": "The Accounting Method spreads the cost of operations by charging each operation, possibly more than its actual cost, to cover the expensive operations in the sequence."
  }
]
