        "content": "[\n    {\n        \"question\": \"How is the accounting method used in the dynamic array example to handle array resizing costs?\",\n        \"answer\": \"In the dynamic array example, the accounting method assigns extra charges to inexpensive insertions so that the surplus can cover the costly resizing operations. Specifically, each insertion operation is charged more than its actual cost; the extra units collected from earlier cheap insertions are saved to 'pay for' the expensive resizing when the array grows. This ensures that while some operations are expensive, the amortized or average cost per insertion remains low over a sequence of operations. The key point of this method is to spread the high cost of resizing evenly across all insertions, making the data structure efficient in the long run.\"\n    },\n    {\n        \"question\": \"How does the accounting method ensure every bit flip in a binary counter is adequately paid for?\",\n        \"answer\": \"In the binary counter example, the accounting method charges 2 units each time a bit flips from 0 to 1, even though flipping a bit only costs 1 unit. The extra unit is stored as a 'credit' with that bit. When the bit is flipped back from 1 to 0, the stored credit is used to pay for this operation, ensuring every flip is covered. This system guarantees that no bit ever lacks sufficient credit to flip, allowing the total cost of a sequence of bit flips (like incrementing a binary counter many times) to be spread out evenly. The key takeaway is that this method balances expensive and cheap operations, so the amortized cost per increment remains constant.\"\n    }\n]",
