2025-05-27 00:45:45,039 - __main__ - DEBUG - Generated flashcards: [
  {
    "question": "Why do we overcharge some operations in amortized analysis?",
    "answer": "We overcharge some operations early in order to create a reserve of prepaid charge that can be used later to pay for more expensive operations, ensuring the average cost across all operations remains balanced."
  },
  {
    "question": "How is prepaid charge used in the context of amortized analysis?",
    "answer": "A prepaid charge collected from earlier overcharged operations is set aside and later used to pay for other operations when their actual cost exceeds their assigned amortized cost."
  },
  {
    "question": "What is the Aggregate Method in amortized analysis and how is the amortized cost per operation calculated?",
    "answer": "The Aggregate Method first analyzes the entire sequence of operations, then calculates the amortized cost per operation by dividing the total cost T(n) of n operations by n. It determines an upper bound on the total sequence of n operations, and the amortized cost is T(n)/n, giving an average per operation even if individual operations vary in cost. This method applies the average cost to every operation in the sequence, even if they are of different types."
  },
  {
    "question": "How does the Accounting Method assign and use amortized costs in algorithm analysis?",
    "answer": "The Accounting Method first assigns an amortized cost to each operation, ensuring that the total of these amortized costs is at least the sum of the actual costs of all operations in the sequence. For each operation: if amortized cost exceeds actual cost, the surplus is stored as credit with an object in the data structure; if actual cost exceeds amortized cost, stored credits are used to pay the difference. This guarantees that the total amortized cost is an upper bound on the total real cost, and ensures no probability is involved in the analysis."
  },
  {
    "question": "How does the accounting method apply to a dynamic array?",
    "answer": "In a dynamic array, the accounting method charges extra for cheap insertions to pay for expensive resizing operations, ensuring the total cost is amortized. For example, when an item is inserted and no resizing is needed, more than the actual cost is charged (such as charging 3 when the real cost is 1), accumulating credit that can be used to pay for the occasional expensive resize operation when the array doubles in size. This keeps the amortized cost per insertion operation constant over time, balancing out the infrequent expensive operations with many inexpensive ones."
  },
  {
    "question": "What is an example of amortized analysis in binary counter operations?",
    "answer": "In a binary counter, the accounting method charges 2 units for each bit flip from 0 to 1, using the extra unit to pay for the subsequent flip back to 0. This means that every time a bit is set to 1, a credit is placed on it, which will be used to pay the cost when it needs to be reset to 0 on a future increment. By this method, the cost of incrementing the counter is averaged out, so that the amortized cost per increment remains constant, even though some increments may require flipping multiple bits."
  },
  {
    "question": "How does the Potential Method maintain credit in amortized analysis?",
    "answer": "In the Potential Method, we maintain credit as potential energy associated with the structure as a whole. The cost of each operation is then calculated as T(n)n, where T(n) represents the cost function for the operation. This method analyzes the overall structure to distribute costs across operations."
  },
  {
    "question": "What is the Accounting Method in amortized analysis and how are operations charged?",
    "answer": "The Accounting Method in amortized analysis involves charging the operations individually. Each operation is assigned a specific cost, which may be more or less than its actual execution cost, to balance out expensive and inexpensive operations over a sequence. The total assigned cost over all operations remains an upper bound on the real total cost."
  }
]
