Flashcard 1:
2025-05-29 18:29:36,797 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Question: What is Amortized Analysis?
2025-05-29 18:29:36,797 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Answer: A method to accurately compute the total time spent executing a sequence of operations on a data structure by averaging the time over all operations.
2025-05-29 18:29:36,797 - services.copilot_service - INFO - --------------------------------------------------
2025-05-29 18:29:36,797 - services.copilot_service - INFO - 
Flashcard 2:
2025-05-29 18:29:36,798 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Question: What is the purpose of Amortized Analysis?
2025-05-29 18:29:36,799 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Answer: To guarantee average performance of each operation in a sequence, even if some operations are expensive, without involving probability.
2025-05-29 18:29:36,799 - services.copilot_service - INFO - --------------------------------------------------
2025-05-29 18:29:36,799 - services.copilot_service - INFO - 
Flashcard 3:
2025-05-29 18:29:36,799 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Question: What are the three methods of Amortized Analysis?
2025-05-29 18:29:36,799 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Answer: Aggregate Method, Accounting Method, and Potential Method.
2025-05-29 18:29:36,800 - services.copilot_service - INFO - --------------------------------------------------
2025-05-29 18:29:36,800 - services.copilot_service - INFO - 
Flashcard 4:
2025-05-29 18:29:36,800 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Question: How does the Aggregate Method work?
2025-05-29 18:29:36,800 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Answer: It determines an upper bound T(n) on the total sequence of n operations. The amortized cost per operation is then T(n)/n.
2025-05-29 18:29:36,800 - services.copilot_service - INFO - --------------------------------------------------
2025-05-29 18:29:36,801 - services.copilot_service - INFO - 
Flashcard 5:
2025-05-29 18:29:36,801 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Question: What is the Accounting Method in Amortized Analysis?
2025-05-29 18:29:36,801 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Answer: A method where operations are assigned amortized costs, overcharging some early operations to pay for later ones, ensuring the total amortized cost is an upper bound on the actual cost.
2025-05-29 18:29:36,801 - services.copilot_service - INFO - --------------------------------------------------
2025-05-29 18:29:36,801 - services.copilot_service - INFO - 
Flashcard 6:
2025-05-29 18:29:36,802 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Question: How does the Potential Method work?
2025-05-29 18:29:36,802 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Answer: It uses a potential function to assign amortized costs based on the state of the data structure, ensuring the sum of amortized costs covers the actual costs.
2025-05-29 18:29:36,802 - services.copilot_service - INFO - --------------------------------------------------
2025-05-29 18:29:36,802 - services.copilot_service - INFO - 
Flashcard 7:
2025-05-29 18:29:36,802 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Question: What is the amortized cost formula in the Potential Method?
2025-05-29 18:29:36,935 - services.copilot_service - INFO - --------------------------------------------------
2025-05-29 18:29:36,936 - services.copilot_service - INFO - 
Flashcard 8:
2025-05-29 18:29:36,936 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Question: What is an example of amortized analysis in stack operations?
2025-05-29 18:29:36,936 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Answer: Push and Pop operations have O(1) amortized time, while Multipop has O(1) amortized time per element popped, leading to O(n) total cost for n operations.
2025-05-29 18:29:36,936 - services.copilot_service - INFO - --------------------------------------------------
2025-05-29 18:29:36,936 - services.copilot_service - INFO - 
Flashcard 9:
2025-05-29 18:29:36,937 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Question: How is amortized analysis applied to a k-bit counter?
2025-05-29 18:29:36,937 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Answer: Each bit flip is charged Rs.2 amortized cost, with Rs.1 paying for the flip and Rs.1 stored for later resets, ensuring O(1) amortized cost per increment.
2025-05-29 18:29:36,937 - services.copilot_service - INFO - --------------------------------------------------
2025-05-29 18:29:36,937 - services.copilot_service - INFO - 
Flashcard 10:
2025-05-29 18:29:36,938 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Question: What is the difference between Aggregate and Accounting Methods?
2025-05-29 18:29:36,938 - services.copilot_service - INFO - Answer: Aggregate Method analyzes the entire sequence first, while Accounting Method assigns amortized costs per operation and then computes the total sequence cost.
